        ul.fancy li { margin-bottom: 0.6rem; }
        ul.fancy li::marker { color: #3b82f6; }
        ::-webkit-scrollbar { width: 5px; }
        ::-webkit-scrollbar-track { background: transparent; }
        ::-webkit-scrollbar-thumb { background: rgba(255,255,255,0.1); border-radius: 4px; }
      `}</style>

      <div style={{ display: "flex", minHeight: "100vh", background: "var(--bg)" }}>

        {/* ── SIDEBAR NAV ── */}
        <aside style={{
          width: 240, flexShrink: 0, position: "sticky", top: 0, height: "100vh",
          overflowY: "auto", borderRight: "1px solid var(--border)",
          background: "rgba(3,7,18,0.97)", backdropFilter: "blur(20px)",
          padding: "1.5rem 0", display: "flex", flexDirection: "column"
        }}>
          <div style={{ padding: "0 1.25rem 1.25rem", borderBottom: "1px solid var(--border)", marginBottom: "0.75rem" }}>
            <div style={{ fontSize: "0.65rem", fontWeight: 800, letterSpacing: "0.12em", color: "#475569", marginBottom: "2px", fontFamily: "'Syne', sans-serif" }}>SYSTEM DESIGN</div>
            <div style={{ fontSize: "1rem", fontWeight: 800, color: "#f1f5f9", fontFamily: "'Syne', sans-serif" }}>Foundations</div>
          </div>
          {NAV_TOPICS.map(t => (
            <div key={t.id} className="nav-item"
              onClick={() => scrollTo(t.id)}
              style={{
                padding: "8px 1.25rem", fontSize: "0.82rem", lineHeight: 1.4,
                color: activeSection === t.id ? "#93c5fd" : "#64748b",
                background: activeSection === t.id ? "rgba(59,130,246,0.1)" : "transparent",
                borderLeft: activeSection === t.id ? "3px solid #3b82f6" : "3px solid transparent",
                fontWeight: activeSection === t.id ? 700 : 400,
                fontFamily: activeSection === t.id ? "'Syne', sans-serif" : "inherit"
              }}>
              {t.label}
            </div>
          ))}
        </aside>

        {/* ── MAIN CONTENT ── */}
        <main ref={contentRef} style={{ flex: 1, maxWidth: "860px", margin: "0 auto", padding: "3.5rem 2.5rem 8rem", color: "var(--txt)", lineHeight: 1.8 }}>

          {/* PAGE HEADER */}
          <div style={{ marginBottom: "3.5rem" }}>
            <Pill color="#3b82f6">HLD · FOUNDATIONS</Pill>
            <h1 style={{ fontSize: "2.8rem", fontWeight: 900, color: "#f8fafc", margin: "1rem 0 0.5rem", letterSpacing: "-0.6px", fontFamily: "'Syne', sans-serif", lineHeight: 1.1 }}>
              System Design<br/>Foundations
            </h1>
            <p style={{ color: "#64748b", fontSize: "1.05rem", maxWidth: "600px", margin: 0, lineHeight: 1.7 }}>
              A complete, depth-first guide to every concept, edge case, and design decision that underlies every distributed system ever built.
            </p>
          </div>

          {/* ════════════════════════════════════════════════
              SECTION 1 — REQUIREMENTS ANALYSIS
          ════════════════════════════════════════════════ */}
          <div className="section-card">
            <SH id="req-analysis" icon="🎯" accent="#3b82f6" title="Requirements Analysis"
              subtitle="The single most important skill in system design. Every wrong decision traces back to a poorly understood requirement." />

            <p style={{ color: "#94a3b8" }}>
              Before drawing a single box in your architecture diagram, you must freeze the problem space. Requirements analysis transforms a vague, ambiguous "build a Twitter" prompt into a precise, measurable contract that your system must fulfil. Skipping this step is the #1 reason systems are over-engineered, under-built, or entirely wrong.
            </p>

            <Callout type="note">In a real interview: spend the first 5–8 minutes <strong>only</strong> on requirements. Interviewers reward this discipline heavily. In production: the same rigor prevents wasted engineering months.</Callout>

            <h3 style={{ color: "#e2e8f0", fontFamily: "'Syne', sans-serif", marginTop: "2rem" }}>The Requirement Funnel</h3>
            <p style={{ color: "#94a3b8" }}>Think of requirements as a funnel. Start broad (business goals), narrow to functional behaviour, then drill to non-functional quality attributes, and finally surface all constraints.</p>

            <RefImage
              src="https://miro.medium.com/v2/resize:fit:1400/1*Q5mFIv_pFzS-gMiFqkbKhg.png"
              alt="Requirements funnel from business goals to constraints"
              caption="The requirement funnel: from business objectives down to hard technical constraints"
            />
          </div>

          {/* ════════════════════════════════════════════════
              SECTION 2 — FUNCTIONAL REQUIREMENTS
          ════════════════════════════════════════════════ */}
          <div className="section-card">
            <SH id="functional" icon="⚙️" accent="#22d3ee" title="Functional Requirements"
              subtitle="What the system must DO — the verbs and nouns of your product." />

            <p style={{ color: "#94a3b8" }}>
              Functional requirements describe observable behaviours: user actions, system responses, data transformations. They are unambiguous, testable, and bounded. Good FRs answer: <em>"Given a state, when this event occurs, the system produces this outcome."</em>
            </p>

            <div style={{ display: "grid", gridTemplateColumns: "1fr 1fr", gap: "1rem", margin: "1.5rem 0" }}>
              <div style={{ background: "rgba(34,211,238,0.05)", border: "1px solid rgba(34,211,238,0.2)", borderRadius: "12px", padding: "1.25rem" }}>
                <strong style={{ color: "#67e8f9", display: "block", marginBottom: "8px" }}>✅ Good FR</strong>
                <ul className="fancy" style={{ color: "#94a3b8", paddingLeft: "18px", margin: 0, fontSize: "0.9rem" }}>
                  <li>User can upload a JPEG/PNG ≤ 5 MB and receive a CDN URL within 3 seconds</li>
                  <li>Search returns results ranked by recency within 200 ms for queries under 50 chars</li>
                  <li>A user receives a push notification within 5 seconds of a comment on their post</li>
                </ul>
              </div>
              <div style={{ background: "rgba(248,113,113,0.05)", border: "1px solid rgba(248,113,113,0.2)", borderRadius: "12px", padding: "1.25rem" }}>
                <strong style={{ color: "#fca5a5", display: "block", marginBottom: "8px" }}>❌ Weak FR</strong>
                <ul className="fancy" style={{ color: "#94a3b8", paddingLeft: "18px", margin: 0, fontSize: "0.9rem" }}>
                  <li>"Users can upload images" — no size limit, no format, no SLA</li>
                  <li>"Fast search" — fast is not a requirement</li>
                  <li>"Users get notifications" — channel? delay? dedup?</li>
                </ul>
              </div>
            </div>

            <h3 style={{ color: "#e2e8f0", fontFamily: "'Syne', sans-serif", marginTop: "2rem" }}>CRUD Decomposition Pattern</h3>
            <p style={{ color: "#94a3b8" }}>For data-heavy systems, enumerate every entity and its CRUD surface area. This directly maps to your API design and database schema.</p>

            <Table
              headers={["Entity", "Create", "Read", "Update", "Delete", "Notes"]}
              rows={[
                ["User", "Register", "Profile page", "Edit profile", "Deactivate", "Soft-delete only"],
                ["Post", "Publish", "Feed, Detail", "Edit body", "Hard delete", "Max 280 chars"],
                ["Like", "Like", "Count, check", "—", "Unlike", "Idempotent"],
                ["Follow", "Follow", "Followers list", "—", "Unfollow", "Bi-directional graph"],
              ]}
            />

            <Callout type="warn">
              <strong>Edge case — conflicting FRs:</strong> "Users can edit a post" + "All likes are tied to the original content" creates a conflict. If a user edits text after 1000 likes, do those likes reference the old or new version? Resolve this before design begins.
            </Callout>

            <Callout type="err">
              <strong>Exception — implicit FRs:</strong> Stakeholders assume certain behaviours exist without stating them (e.g., "of course pagination exists"). Always surface implicit FRs explicitly and add them to the written spec.
            </Callout>
          </div>

          {/* ════════════════════════════════════════════════
              SECTION 3 — NON-FUNCTIONAL REQUIREMENTS
          ════════════════════════════════════════════════ */}
          <div className="section-card">
            <SH id="nfr" icon="📐" accent="#a78bfa" title="Non-Functional Requirements (NFRs)"
              subtitle="How the system must BEHAVE under real-world conditions — the adverbs and adjectives of architecture." />

            <p style={{ color: "#94a3b8" }}>
              NFRs define the quality envelope in which your system must operate. They don't describe features — they describe the behaviour of those features at scale, under failure, and over time. NFRs are typically the deciding force behind every major architectural decision: choosing SQL vs NoSQL, sync vs async, monolith vs microservices.
            </p>

            <RefImage
              src="https://learn.microsoft.com/en-us/azure/architecture/guide/images/pillars.png"
              alt="Azure Well-Architected Framework pillars"
              caption="Microsoft's Well-Architected Framework — the industry-standard NFR taxonomy"
            />

            <h3 style={{ color: "#e2e8f0", fontFamily: "'Syne', sans-serif" }}>Quantifying NFRs — Always Use Numbers</h3>
            <p style={{ color: "#94a3b8" }}>An NFR without a number is not an NFR — it's a wish. Every NFR must have a measurable target and a measurable threshold for failure.</p>

            <Table
              headers={["NFR", "Bad (Vague)", "Good (Measurable)", "Measurement Method"]}
              rows={[
                ["Availability", "High availability", "99.99% uptime (52 min downtime/yr)", "External synthetic monitoring"],
                ["Latency", "Fast response", "p99 < 300ms for read APIs", "APM percentile histograms"],
                ["Throughput", "Handle load", "5,000 write TPS sustained", "Load test with Gatling"],
                ["Durability", "Don't lose data", "RPO < 1 minute", "DB replication lag monitoring"],
                ["Error Rate", "Rarely fail", "< 0.01% 5xx rate", "Error budget tracking"],
              ]}
            />

            <Callout type="tip">
              When negotiating NFRs with PMs, use the <strong>SLI → SLO → SLA</strong> framework: <br/>
              <strong>SLI</strong> (Service Level Indicator): the actual metric — e.g., request success rate<br/>
              <strong>SLO</strong> (Service Level Objective): your internal target — e.g., 99.9% over 30 days<br/>
              <strong>SLA</strong> (Service Level Agreement): the contractual promise with penalty — e.g., 99.5% or customer gets credit
            </Callout>
          </div>

          {/* ════════════════════════════════════════════════
              SECTION 4 — SCALABILITY, AVAILABILITY, RELIABILITY
          ════════════════════════════════════════════════ */}
          <div className="section-card">
            <SH id="scalability" icon="📈" accent="#34d399" title="Scalability, Availability & Reliability"
              subtitle="The three pillars that govern whether your system survives real-world usage." />

            {/* SCALABILITY */}
            <h3 style={{ color: "#34d399", fontFamily: "'Syne', sans-serif", fontSize: "1.2rem" }}>Scalability</h3>
            <p style={{ color: "#94a3b8" }}>
              Scalability is the system's ability to handle <em>increasing load</em> without degradation in performance, by adding resources proportionally. There are two fundamental axes of scaling:
            </p>

            <div style={{ display: "grid", gridTemplateColumns: "1fr 1fr", gap: "1rem", margin: "1rem 0" }}>
              <InfoBox color="#34d399" icon="↔️" title="Horizontal Scaling (Scale Out)">
                Adding more machines/nodes to a pool. The industry-preferred approach for stateless services. Requires load balancing, distributed state management, and often eventual consistency trade-offs.
                <br/><br/><strong style={{ color: "#a7f3d0" }}>Examples:</strong> Adding more web servers behind a load balancer, adding read replicas to a database.
              </InfoBox>
              <InfoBox color="#fbbf24" icon="↕️" title="Vertical Scaling (Scale Up)">
                Increasing the resources (CPU, RAM, disk) of an existing machine. Simple but has a hard ceiling (largest machine available) and introduces a single point of failure. No code changes needed.
                <br/><br/><strong style={{ color: "#fde68a" }}>Examples:</strong> Upgrading from db.r5.large to db.r5.4xlarge on RDS.
              </InfoBox>
            </div>

            <h4 style={{ color: "#e2e8f0", fontFamily: "'Syne', sans-serif" }}>Read/Write Scaling Patterns</h4>
            <Table
              headers={["Pattern", "What it solves", "Trade-off", "When to use"]}
              rows={[
                ["Read Replicas", "Read-heavy workloads (e.g. 95% reads)", "Replication lag → stale reads", "Social feeds, product catalogs"],
                ["Write Sharding", "Write throughput limits", "Cross-shard queries become complex", "User data partitioned by user_id"],
                ["CQRS", "Separate read/write models", "Dual schema maintenance", "Event-sourced systems"],
                ["Caching Layer", "Reduce DB read QPS by 90–99%", "Cache invalidation complexity", "Almost always"],
              ]}
            />

            <Callout type="warn">
              <strong>Stateful vs Stateless scaling:</strong> Stateless services scale trivially (each instance is identical). Stateful services (like WebSocket servers or in-memory session stores) require sticky sessions or external state stores (Redis). Always architect your app tier to be stateless; push state into dedicated stores.
            </Callout>

            <RefImage
              src="https://bytebytego.com/images/courses/system-design-interview/scale-from-zero-to-millions-of-users/figure-1-23.png"
              alt="Scaling from single server to millions of users"
              caption="Progressive scaling architecture: from a single server to a globally distributed system"
            />

            {/* AVAILABILITY */}
            <h3 style={{ color: "#60a5fa", fontFamily: "'Syne', sans-serif", fontSize: "1.2rem", marginTop: "2.5rem" }}>Availability</h3>
            <p style={{ color: "#94a3b8" }}>
              Availability = <Code>Uptime / (Uptime + Downtime)</Code>. Expressed as "nines" — the number of 9s in the percentage.
            </p>

            <Table
              headers={["Availability", "Annual Downtime", "Monthly Downtime", "Notes"]}
              rows={[
                ["99% (2 nines)", "87.6 hours", "7.3 hours", "Acceptable for internal tools"],
                ["99.9% (3 nines)", "8.76 hours", "43.8 minutes", "Many web apps"],
                ["99.99% (4 nines)", "52.6 minutes", "4.4 minutes", "Payment systems, SaaS platforms"],
                ["99.999% (5 nines)", "5.26 minutes", "26 seconds", "Telecom, trading systems"],
                ["99.9999% (6 nines)", "31.5 seconds", "2.6 seconds", "Flight control, hospital systems"],
              ]}
            />

            <h4 style={{ color: "#e2e8f0", fontFamily: "'Syne', sans-serif" }}>Availability in Series vs Parallel</h4>
            <p style={{ color: "#94a3b8" }}>When components are in series (all must be up), availability <em>multiplies</em> — it degrades. When in parallel (redundancy), availability <em>improves</em>.</p>
            <CodeBlock>{`Series:   A(total) = A1 × A2 × A3
          A = 0.999 × 0.999 × 0.999 = 0.997 (lost a nine!)

Parallel: A(total) = 1 − (1 − A1) × (1 − A2)
          A = 1 − (0.001 × 0.001) = 0.999999 (6 nines!)`}</CodeBlock>

            <Callout type="tip">
              This math explains why redundancy (N+1, active-active, multi-AZ deployments) is non-negotiable for high-availability systems. Every serial dependency is an availability tax.
            </Callout>

            {/* RELIABILITY */}
            <h3 style={{ color: "#f472b6", fontFamily: "'Syne', sans-serif", fontSize: "1.2rem", marginTop: "2.5rem" }}>Reliability</h3>
            <p style={{ color: "#94a3b8" }}>
              Reliability = probability the system performs its intended function correctly over a specified time period without failure. Different from availability: a system can be <em>available</em> (up) but <em>unreliable</em> (returning wrong results, dropping data).
            </p>
            <InfoBox color="#f472b6" icon="🔁" title="MTBF and MTTR">
              <strong>MTBF</strong> (Mean Time Between Failures): average time between incidents. Maximize this by reducing failure causes.
              <br/><strong>MTTR</strong> (Mean Time To Recovery): average time to restore service after failure. Minimize this via runbooks, automation, and health checks.
              <br/><br/><Code>Availability ≈ MTBF / (MTBF + MTTR)</Code> — Improving either metric improves availability.
            </InfoBox>
            <Callout type="err">
              <strong>The Reliability Trap:</strong> Systems often degrade gracefully rather than fail hard, making reliability issues invisible in uptime metrics. A search engine that returns stale results is "available" but unreliable. Build correctness checks, not just ping checks.
            </Callout>
          </div>

          {/* ════════════════════════════════════════════════
              SECTION 5 — CONSISTENCY, LATENCY, DURABILITY
          ════════════════════════════════════════════════ */}
          <div className="section-card">
            <SH id="consistency" icon="⚖️" accent="#fb923c" title="Consistency, Latency & Durability"
              subtitle="The trio at the heart of every distributed systems trade-off." />

            {/* CONSISTENCY */}
            <h3 style={{ color: "#fb923c", fontFamily: "'Syne', sans-serif", fontSize: "1.2rem" }}>Consistency</h3>
            <p style={{ color: "#94a3b8" }}>
              In a distributed system, consistency means every node sees the same data at the same time. The CAP theorem forces a choice between consistency and availability during a network partition. But consistency itself has a spectrum:
            </p>

            <RefImage
              src="https://systemdesign.one/images/consistency-spectrum.png"
              alt="Consistency spectrum from strong to eventual"
              caption="The consistency spectrum — from strict linearizability to eventual consistency"
            />

            <Table
              headers={["Model", "Guarantee", "Latency", "Use Case"]}
              rows={[
                ["Linearizability (Strong)", "Operations appear instantaneous & sequential", "High (sync writes)", "Bank transfers, inventory counters"],
                ["Sequential Consistency", "All processes see same order, not real-time", "Medium", "Distributed coordination"],
                ["Causal Consistency", "Causally related ops seen in order", "Medium-low", "Collaborative apps"],
                ["Read-your-writes", "After write, you always read your own write", "Low", "User profile updates"],
                ["Monotonic Read", "Once you read a value, you never see older", "Low", "News feeds"],
                ["Eventual Consistency", "All replicas converge — no timing guarantee", "Very low", "DNS, shopping carts"],
              ]}
            />

            <Callout type="warn">
              <strong>CAP Theorem Edge Cases:</strong> The CAP theorem's "partition" is often misunderstood. Network partitions are rare but inevitable. The real question is: during the seconds of a partition, do you serve stale data (AP) or return an error (CP)? Most internet systems choose AP with compensating mechanisms (e.g., version vectors, conflict-free replicated data types / CRDTs).
            </Callout>

            <h4 style={{ color: "#e2e8f0", fontFamily: "'Syne', sans-serif" }}>PACELC — The Extended Model</h4>
            <InfoBox color="#fb923c" icon="🔬" title="PACELC">
              PACELC extends CAP: even when there is <strong>no partition (P)</strong>, you still trade off <strong>availability vs consistency (A/C)</strong>. And <strong>else (E)</strong> — during normal operation — you trade off <strong>latency vs consistency (L/C)</strong>. This is more realistic for daily system design decisions.
            </InfoBox>

            {/* LATENCY */}
            <h3 style={{ color: "#7dd3fc", fontFamily: "'Syne', sans-serif", fontSize: "1.2rem", marginTop: "2.5rem" }}>Latency</h3>
            <p style={{ color: "#94a3b8" }}>
              Latency is the time from a client sending a request to receiving the first byte of response. It is NOT throughput. You must track <strong>percentiles</strong>, not averages — p99 latency is what your worst 1% of users experience.
            </p>

            <RefImage
              src="https://i.imgur.com/K0t390b.png"
              alt="Latency numbers every programmer should know"
              caption="Latency numbers every programmer should know — Peter Norvig / Jeff Dean"
            />

            <CodeBlock>{`Operation                          Latency
─────────────────────────────────────────────
L1 cache reference                 0.5 ns
Branch mispredict                  5 ns
L2 cache reference                 7 ns
Mutex lock/unlock                  25 ns
Main memory reference              100 ns
Compress 1KB (Snappy)              3,000 ns   (3 µs)
Send 1KB over 1 Gbps network       10,000 ns  (10 µs)
Read 4KB randomly from SSD         150,000 ns (150 µs)
Read 1MB sequentially from memory  250,000 ns (250 µs)
Round trip within same datacenter  500,000 ns (0.5 ms)
Read 1MB sequentially from SSD     1,000,000  (1 ms)
Disk seek                          10,000,000 (10 ms)
Read 1MB sequentially from HDD     30,000,000 (30 ms)
Send packet CA → Netherlands → CA  150,000,000 (150 ms)`}</CodeBlock>

            <Callout type="tip">
              Memory is 200× faster than SSD. SSD is 5,000× faster than HDD. Network within a DC is 10× slower than memory. These numbers explain why caching, SSD-first storage, and regional architecture all matter enormously.
            </Callout>

            {/* DURABILITY */}
            <h3 style={{ color: "#a78bfa", fontFamily: "'Syne', sans-serif", fontSize: "1.2rem", marginTop: "2.5rem" }}>Durability</h3>
            <p style={{ color: "#94a3b8" }}>
              Durability guarantees that once a transaction is committed, it survives crashes, power failures, and hardware faults. It's the 'D' in ACID.
            </p>

            <InfoBox color="#a78bfa" icon="💾" title="Durability Mechanisms">
              <strong>Write-Ahead Log (WAL):</strong> Every write is first journalled to append-only log before applying. On crash, replay the WAL.<br/>
              <strong>Replication:</strong> Write to 2 or 3 nodes synchronously before acknowledging the client (e.g., Raft's quorum writes).<br/>
              <strong>Checksums:</strong> Detect silent data corruption — write hash alongside data, verify on read.<br/>
              <strong>Backup + Point-in-Time Recovery:</strong> Periodic full backups + continuous WAL shipping to S3.
            </InfoBox>

            <Table
              headers={["Durability Level", "Mechanism", "RPO", "Cost"]}
              rows={[
                ["No durability", "In-memory only (Redis default)", "All data on crash", "Lowest"],
                ["Single-node persist", "Local WAL + fsync", "Last checkpoint (~1s)", "Low"],
                ["Sync replication", "Quorum writes (2+ nodes)", "~0 (last committed tx)", "Medium"],
                ["Multi-region replication", "Async + sync cross-region", "~0 to minutes", "High"],
                ["Immutable backups", "S3 versioned + Glacier", "Depends on backup freq", "Variable"],
              ]}
            />
          </div>

          {/* ════════════════════════════════════════════════
              SECTION 6 — SECURITY
          ════════════════════════════════════════════════ */}
          <div className="section-card">
            <SH id="security" icon="🔐" accent="#f43f5e" title="Security"
              subtitle="Security is not a feature — it's a property that must be baked in from requirements, not bolted on after." />

            <p style={{ color: "#94a3b8" }}>Security NFRs are often the most neglected in system design discussions, yet they have the highest blast radius when violated. Treat security as a first-class architectural concern.</p>

            <h3 style={{ color: "#e2e8f0", fontFamily: "'Syne', sans-serif" }}>Security Dimensions</h3>
            <div style={{ display: "grid", gridTemplateColumns: "1fr 1fr", gap: "1rem", margin: "1rem 0" }}>
