              SECTION 8 — CAPACITY ESTIMATION
          ════════════════════════════════════════════════ */}
          <div className="section-card">
            <SH id="capacity" icon="🧮" accent="#06b6d4" title="Capacity Estimation"
              subtitle="Back-of-the-envelope math that reveals architectural requirements before a single line of code is written." />

            <p style={{ color: "#94a3b8" }}>
              Capacity estimation converts user-level requirements into infrastructure-level numbers. The goal is not precision — it's <em>order of magnitude</em> accuracy. Being off by 2× is fine. Being off by 1000× means you'll choose the wrong architecture.
            </p>

            <h3 style={{ color: "#e2e8f0", fontFamily: "'Syne', sans-serif" }}>The Estimation Toolkit</h3>

            <Table
              headers={["Unit", "Value", "Memory Aid"]}
              rows={[
                ["1 KB", "10³ bytes", "A short paragraph of text"],
                ["1 MB", "10⁶ bytes", "A JPEG thumbnail"],
                ["1 GB", "10⁹ bytes", "A movie (compressed)"],
                ["1 TB", "10¹² bytes", "1,000 movies"],
                ["1 PB", "10¹⁵ bytes", "All US academic research libraries"],
                ["1 day", "86,400 seconds", "~100K seconds (useful approximation)"],
                ["1 month", "2.6M seconds", "~2.5M seconds"],
                ["1 year", "31.5M seconds", "~30M seconds"],
              ]}
            />

            <h3 style={{ color: "#e2e8f0", fontFamily: "'Syne', sans-serif", marginTop: "2rem" }}>Worked Example: Twitter-Scale Feed</h3>

            <CodeBlock>{`Assumptions:
  500M registered users, 100M DAU
  Average user: follows 200 accounts, 2 reads/day, 0.1 writes/day

Traffic Estimation:
  Write QPS = 100M × 0.1 / 86400 ≈ 116 QPS (avg)
  Read QPS  = 100M × 2   / 86400 ≈ 2,314 QPS (avg)
  Peak QPS  = 2,314 × 3          ≈ 7,000 QPS (peak reads) 
  Read:Write ratio ≈ 20:1  →  this is a READ-HEAVY system

Storage Estimation:
  Tweet size = 140 chars × 2 bytes (UTF-16) + metadata = ~500 bytes
  New tweets/day = 100M × 0.1 = 10M tweets/day
  Daily storage = 10M × 500 bytes = 5 GB/day
  5-year storage = 5 GB × 365 × 5 ≈ 9 TB
  → Single DB can handle this. Sharding needed for QPS, not storage.

Media Estimation (images/videos):
  20% of tweets have media, avg 200 KB
  Daily media = 10M × 0.2 × 200 KB = 400 GB/day
  5-year media = 400 GB × 365 × 5 ≈ 730 TB ≈ 0.7 PB
  → Blob storage (S3) + CDN mandatory.

Bandwidth:
  Read bandwidth = 7,000 QPS × 1 KB (avg response) = 7 MB/s
  → Trivial for a CDN. No bottleneck here.

Cache Estimation:
  80/20 rule: 20% of tweets generate 80% of reads
  Hot tweets to cache = 10M × 20% = 2M tweets
  Cache size = 2M × 500 bytes = 1 GB/day
  → Fits comfortably in Redis (128 GB cache node serves weeks of hot data)`}</CodeBlock>

            <Callout type="note">
              The <strong>read:write ratio</strong> is the most important output of capacity estimation. A 20:1 ratio immediately suggests: read replicas, aggressive caching, CDN, eventual consistency for reads. A 1:10 write-heavy ratio suggests: LSM-tree based storage (Cassandra, RocksDB), write buffering, async persistence.
            </Callout>

            <RefImage
              src="https://bytebytego.com/images/courses/system-design-interview/back-of-the-envelope-estimation/powers-of-2.png"
              alt="Powers of 2 reference table"
              caption="Powers of 2 — commit these to memory for instant estimation"
            />

            <Callout type="warn">
              <strong>Estimation Traps:</strong><br/>
              1. <strong>Forgetting peak multiplier:</strong> Always multiply avg QPS by 2–5× for peak.<br/>
              2. <strong>Ignoring replication overhead:</strong> 3-replica storage = 3× raw storage cost.<br/>
              3. <strong>Confusing ingress vs egress:</strong> A video platform reads 100× more than it writes — bandwidth is dominated by egress.<br/>
              4. <strong>Single-node bias:</strong> Always check if a single machine can handle the numbers before adding complexity.
            </Callout>
          </div>

