          <div className="section-card">
            <SH id="dry-kiss-yagni" icon="💎" accent="#22d3ee" title="DRY, KISS & YAGNI"
              subtitle="The three principles that fight complexity before it takes root." />

            <h3 style={{ color: "#22d3ee", fontFamily: "'Syne', sans-serif" }}>DRY — Don't Repeat Yourself</h3>
            <p style={{ color: "#94a3b8" }}>
              "Every piece of knowledge must have a single, unambiguous, authoritative representation within a system." — The Pragmatic Programmer.
            </p>
            <p style={{ color: "#94a3b8" }}>
              DRY is about <em>knowledge</em> duplication, not code duplication. The same business rule appearing in two places is DRY-violation even if the code looks different. Two similar-looking functions that evolve independently for different reasons are NOT a DRY violation.
            </p>
            <InfoBox color="#22d3ee" icon="🔁" title="DRY in Distributed Systems">
              In microservices, DRY manifests as shared libraries for common logic (auth validation, date formatting). But over-applying DRY by creating a "common" library that all services depend on creates a distributed monolith — a change to that library forces redeployment of all services. Prefer duplication over wrong abstraction.
            </InfoBox>
            <Callout type="warn">
              The <strong>Rule of Three:</strong> Don't abstract the first time you see duplication, don't abstract the second time, but on the third occurrence, extract to a shared abstraction. Premature DRY creates the wrong abstraction which is worse than duplication.
            </Callout>

            <h3 style={{ color: "#a78bfa", fontFamily: "'Syne', sans-serif", marginTop: "2rem" }}>KISS — Keep It Simple, Stupid</h3>
            <p style={{ color: "#94a3b8" }}>
              Systems should be as simple as possible, but no simpler. Complexity is the #1 enemy of reliability, debuggability, and onboarding velocity.
            </p>
            <Table
              headers={["Complexity Source", "KISS Remedy"]}
              rows={[
                ["10 microservices for a 2-person team", "Start with a modular monolith, split when you have specific bottlenecks"],
                ["Custom distributed lock from scratch", "Use Redis SETNX or Zookeeper — the hard cases are already solved"],
                ["Premature event sourcing", "Use simple CRUD + an audit log table until event sourcing is truly required"],
                ["Hand-rolled consensus algorithm", "Use etcd, Raft-based stores, or PostgreSQL with transactions"],
                ["Over-normalized schema (7 joins)", "Denormalize read tables or use CQRS for read models"],
              ]}
            />
            <Callout type="tip">
              <strong>Einstein's Razor for Architecture:</strong> "Everything should be made as simple as possible, but not simpler." The cost of over-simplification (missing necessary abstractions) is just as real as over-engineering.
            </Callout>

            <h3 style={{ color: "#f472b6", fontFamily: "'Syne', sans-serif", marginTop: "2rem" }}>YAGNI — You Aren't Gonna Need It</h3>
            <p style={{ color: "#94a3b8" }}>
              Don't implement something until it is actually needed. Speculative features and pre-emptive scaling consume engineering resources and often turn out to be wrong when the real need eventually arrives.
            </p>
            <div style={{ display: "grid", gridTemplateColumns: "1fr 1fr", gap: "1rem", margin: "1rem 0" }}>
              <div style={{ background: "rgba(244,114,182,0.06)", border: "1px solid rgba(244,114,182,0.2)", borderRadius: "12px", padding: "1.25rem" }}>
                <strong style={{ color: "#f9a8d4", display: "block", marginBottom: "8px" }}>🚫 YAGNI Violations</strong>
                <ul className="fancy" style={{ color: "#94a3b8", paddingLeft: "18px", margin: 0, fontSize: "0.9rem" }}>
                  <li>Building multi-tenancy before you have a second customer</li>
                  <li>Adding a message queue for 100 users/day because "we'll need it eventually"</li>
                  <li>Implementing GraphQL when REST with 2 endpoints covers all use cases</li>
                  <li>Building an ML recommendation engine before validating product-market fit</li>
                </ul>
              </div>
              <div style={{ background: "rgba(52,211,153,0.06)", border: "1px solid rgba(52,211,153,0.2)", borderRadius: "12px", padding: "1.25rem" }}>
                <strong style={{ color: "#6ee7b7", display: "block", marginBottom: "8px" }}>✅ YAGNI-Respecting Approach</strong>
                <ul className="fancy" style={{ color: "#94a3b8", paddingLeft: "18px", margin: 0, fontSize: "0.9rem" }}>
                  <li>Deploy a single PostgreSQL instance — add sharding when you hit limits</li>
                  <li>Synchronous in-process calls — extract to async when latency requirements demand it</li>
                  <li>Single application server — add load balancing at 10K DAU</li>
                  <li>Monolith first — split services at team/scaling boundaries</li>
                </ul>
              </div>
            </div>
            <Callout type="err">
              <strong>Exception — Security and Compliance:</strong> YAGNI does NOT apply to security or regulatory compliance. You must build auth, encryption, audit logging, and data residency from day one. Retrofitting security is 10× harder than building it in.
            </Callout>
          </div>

          {/* ════════════════════════════════════════════════
              SECTION 12 — SEPARATION OF CONCERNS
          ════════════════════════════════════════════════ */}
          <div className="section-card">
            <SH id="soc" icon="🗂️" accent="#fbbf24" title="Separation of Concerns"
              subtitle="The architectural force that keeps systems comprehensible as they grow." />

            <p style={{ color: "#94a3b8" }}>
              Separation of Concerns (SoC) mandates that each module, layer, or service handles one distinct concern of the system, with minimal knowledge of other concerns. It's the architectural expression of cognitive limit management — humans can hold ~7 concepts in working memory at once.
            </p>

            <h3 style={{ color: "#e2e8f0", fontFamily: "'Syne', sans-serif" }}>Layered Architecture (The Classic SoC Pattern)</h3>
            <RefImage
              src="https://herbertograca.com/wp-content/uploads/2017/04/layered-arch-1.png"
              alt="Classic layered architecture diagram"
              caption="Classic N-Tier layered architecture — the textbook application of Separation of Concerns"
            />

            <Table
              headers={["Layer", "Responsibility", "Should NOT Know About"]}
              rows={[
                ["Presentation (UI)", "Render data, handle user input, routing", "Database schemas, business rules"],
                ["Application (Use Cases)", "Orchestrate business flows, transaction boundaries", "HTTP, SQL, UI framework"],
                ["Domain (Business Logic)", "Core entities, invariants, domain events", "Databases, HTTP, UI"],
                ["Infrastructure", "DB access, external APIs, messaging, file I/O", "Business rules, UI"],
              ]}
            />

            <h3 style={{ color: "#e2e8f0", fontFamily: "'Syne', sans-serif", marginTop: "2rem" }}>SoC in Distributed Systems</h3>
            <InfoBox color="#fbbf24" icon="🔭" title="Cross-Cutting Concerns">
              Some concerns span all layers: logging, security, caching, and error handling. These should be handled via cross-cutting mechanisms (middleware, AOP, decorators) rather than scattered throughout business logic. A security check inside a domain entity is a SoC violation.
            </InfoBox>
            <Callout type="warn">
              <strong>The God Object Anti-Pattern:</strong> A class/service that knows about the database, handles HTTP parsing, runs business rules, sends emails, AND manages caching is the textbook SoC violation. God objects are the #1 source of "just one more change breaks everything" in production systems.
            </Callout>
          </div>

          {/* ════════════════════════════════════════════════
              SECTION 13 — LOOSE VS TIGHT COUPLING
          ════════════════════════════════════════════════ */}
          <div className="section-card">
            <SH id="coupling" icon="🔗" accent="#f87171" title="Loose vs Tight Coupling"
              subtitle="The degree to which components know about and depend on each other's internal implementation." />

            <p style={{ color: "#94a3b8" }}>
              Coupling measures dependency. Tightly coupled systems are rigid, fragile, and hard to test. Loosely coupled systems are flexible, resilient, and independently deployable.
            </p>

            <RefImage
              src="https://miro.medium.com/v2/resize:fit:1400/1*zAMIHFPNlZJhBFP3V4fNQA.png"
              alt="Tight vs loose coupling diagram"
              caption="Tight coupling (left) vs loose coupling (right) — the difference between a change requiring 1 edit vs 20"
            />

            <div style={{ display: "grid", gridTemplateColumns: "1fr 1fr", gap: "1rem", margin: "1rem 0" }}>
              <div style={{ background: "rgba(248,113,113,0.06)", border: "1px solid rgba(248,113,113,0.2)", borderRadius: "12px", padding: "1.25rem" }}>
                <strong style={{ color: "#fca5a5", display: "block", marginBottom: "8px", fontFamily: "'Syne', sans-serif" }}>🔴 Tight Coupling Symptoms</strong>
                <ul className="fancy" style={{ color: "#94a3b8", paddingLeft: "18px", margin: 0, fontSize: "0.9rem" }}>
                  <li>Directly instantiating dependencies (<Code>new EmailService()</Code>)</li>
                  <li>Sharing a database between two services</li>
                  <li>Synchronous HTTP calls deep in call stacks</li>
                  <li>Exposing internal data models in public APIs</li>
                  <li>Feature flags scattered across multiple services</li>
                </ul>
              </div>
              <div style={{ background: "rgba(34,197,94,0.06)", border: "1px solid rgba(34,197,94,0.2)", borderRadius: "12px", padding: "1.25rem" }}>
                <strong style={{ color: "#86efac", display: "block", marginBottom: "8px", fontFamily: "'Syne', sans-serif" }}>🟢 Loose Coupling Techniques</strong>
                <ul className="fancy" style={{ color: "#94a3b8", paddingLeft: "18px", margin: 0, fontSize: "0.9rem" }}>
                  <li>Depend on interfaces, inject concrete implementations</li>
                  <li>Communicate via events/messages (Kafka, SNS)</li>
                  <li>API versioning and backward-compatible contracts</li>
                  <li>Service mesh for runtime decoupling (circuit breakers)</li>
                  <li>Anti-corruption layers between bounded contexts</li>
                </ul>
              </div>
            </div>

            <h3 style={{ color: "#e2e8f0", fontFamily: "'Syne', sans-serif" }}>Types of Coupling (Ordered Worst to Best)</h3>
            <Table
              headers={["Type", "Description", "Example", "Verdict"]}
              rows={[
                ["Content Coupling", "Module modifies internal data of another", "Service A writes directly to Service B's DB table", "🚫 Never"],
                ["Common Coupling", "Shared global state or global variables", "Both services read/write a single global config object", "🚫 Avoid"],
                ["Control Coupling", "Pass flags to control another module's behaviour", "processOrder(order, skipValidation=true)", "⚠️ Smell"],
                ["Data Coupling", "Pass only necessary data via parameters", "createUser({ name, email })", "✅ Acceptable"],
                ["Message Coupling", "Communicate only via messages/events", "order.placed event consumed independently", "✅ Best"],
              ]}
            />

            <Callout type="err">
              <strong>Distributed Monolith:</strong> The worst of both worlds — microservices that are tightly coupled via synchronous HTTP chains. If Service A calls B calls C calls D in a chain, any failure cascades and deployments must be coordinated. You have the operational complexity of microservices with none of the independence benefits.
            </Callout>
          </div>

          {/* ════════════════════════════════════════════════
              SECTION 14 — HIGH COHESION
          ════════════════════════════════════════════════ */}
          <div className="section-card">
            <SH id="cohesion" icon="🧲" accent="#34d399" title="High Cohesion"
              subtitle="The degree to which elements within a module belong together and work toward a single, well-defined purpose." />

            <p style={{ color: "#94a3b8" }}>
              Cohesion is the internal counterpart to coupling. While coupling describes external dependencies, cohesion describes internal unity. A highly cohesive module does one thing, and all of its methods/functions contribute to that one thing.
            </p>

            <InfoBox color="#34d399" icon="🧲" title="The Cohesion-Coupling Duality">
              High cohesion and loose coupling are complementary and mutually reinforcing. A module that does one thing well (high cohesion) naturally has fewer external dependencies (loose coupling). A god class that does everything (low cohesion) is inevitably coupled to everything (tight coupling). <strong>They always move together.</strong>
            </InfoBox>

            <h3 style={{ color: "#e2e8f0", fontFamily: "'Syne', sans-serif" }}>Types of Cohesion (Ordered Best to Worst)</h3>
            <Table
              headers={["Type", "Description", "Example"]}
              rows={[
                ["Functional (Best)", "All elements contribute to a single, well-defined task", "parseJSON(str) — does exactly one thing"],
                ["Sequential", "Output of one element feeds next", "readFile → parseContent → validateSchema"],
                ["Communicational", "Elements operate on same data set", "UserProfile: getName, getEmail, getAge"],
                ["Procedural", "Elements follow a certain sequence/protocol", "startup: init → connect → warmup → listen"],
                ["Temporal", "Elements grouped because they execute at the same time", "onStartup: initLogger, loadConfig, startHealthCheck"],
                ["Logical", "Elements perform similar operations, selected by flag", "handleIO(type): if csv / if json / if xml"],
                ["Coincidental (Worst)", "Elements grouped arbitrarily (utility classes)", "Utils.java with 200 unrelated static methods"],
              ]}
            />

            <h3 style={{ color: "#e2e8f0", fontFamily: "'Syne', sans-serif", marginTop: "2rem" }}>Cohesion in Microservices (Bounded Contexts)</h3>
            <p style={{ color: "#94a3b8" }}>
              In DDD (Domain-Driven Design), a <strong>Bounded Context</strong> is the microservice equivalent of high cohesion. Each service owns a complete, internally consistent model of its domain. The boundary is drawn where concepts from one domain would be confusing in another.
            </p>

            <CodeBlock>{`// HIGH COHESION — OrderService owns the full order lifecycle
OrderService:
  ├── placeOrder(cart)         // create domain event
  ├── cancelOrder(id)         // validate & cancel
  ├── getOrderStatus(id)      // read own data
  ├── applyDiscount(id, code) // own business rule
  └── processReturn(id)       // own lifecycle

// LOW COHESION — OrderService has no coherent identity
OrderService:
  ├── placeOrder(cart)         // orders
  ├── sendConfirmationEmail()  // notifications (different domain!)
  ├── chargeCard()             // payments (different domain!)
  ├── updateInventory()        // warehouse (different domain!)
  └── generateInvoicePDF()     // billing (different domain!)`}</CodeBlock>

            <Callout type="tip">
              <strong>The "Tell, Don't Ask" heuristic for cohesion:</strong> If you find yourself asking an object for its data and then making decisions about it elsewhere, that logic probably belongs inside the object. When external code needs to inspect internals to make decisions, cohesion is breaking down.
            </Callout>

            <Callout type="warn">
              <strong>The Cohesion-Granularity Trade-off:</strong> Extreme cohesion (one function per service) produces a NanoService anti-pattern — thousands of services with trivial functionality. The network overhead, operational burden, and distributed transaction complexity far outweigh the cohesion benefit. Find the right granularity at business domain boundaries, not technical function boundaries.
            </Callout>
          </div>

          {/* FOOTER */}
          <div style={{ marginTop: "3rem", padding: "2rem", background: "rgba(59,130,246,0.05)", border: "1px solid rgba(59,130,246,0.2)", borderRadius: "16px", textAlign: "center" }}>
            <div style={{ fontSize: "0.75rem", fontWeight: 800, letterSpacing: "0.1em", color: "#3b82f6", fontFamily: "'Syne', sans-serif", marginBottom: "0.5rem" }}>FURTHER READING</div>
